    <item>
      <title>Alpine Divorce: A Hike That Ends a Relationship</title>
      <link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/12/style/alpine-divorce-relationships-hike.html</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/12/style/alpine-divorce-relationships-hike.html</guid>
      <atom:link href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/04/12/style/alpine-divorce-relationships-hike.html" rel="standout"></atom:link>
      <description>The “Alpine divorce,” in which one partner leaves another stranded while hiking, is more serious than the name implies.</description>
      <dc:creator>Valeriya Safronova</dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Sun, 12 Apr 2026 18:29:23 +0000</pubDate>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Hikes and Hiking</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Accidents and Safety</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Dating and Relationships</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Marriages</category>
      <media:content height="1800" medium="image" url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/04/12/multimedia/12ST-ALPINE-DIVORCE-btzk/12ST-ALPINE-DIVORCE-btzk-mediumSquareAt3X.jpg" width="1800"></media:content>
      <media:credit>Getty Images</media:credit>
      <media:description>Hiking guides and mountain rescue workers say what’s now being called “Alpine divorce” isn’t new. They’ve been seeing it for years. Long before it became a social media buzzword, they would often have to rescue women left behind on remote and often dangerous trails.</media:description>
    </item>
